{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28acdf1c1ffeHnkpUNmVuE19mJ","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d75322033001p4lvZtSVNt2m6b","parts":[{"id":"prt_d753225fe001ezguilwIzk7bJZ","messageID":"msg_d75322033001p4lvZtSVNt2m6b","sessionID":"ses_28acdf1c1ffeHnkpUNmVuE19mJ","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_a9bf457a61ed460291c487dd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: ======================================================\n2: smart_open — utils for streaming large files in Python\n3: ======================================================\n4: \n5: \n6: |License|_ |CI|_ |Coveralls|_ |Version|_ |Python|_ |Downloads|_\n7: \n8: .. |License| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/smart_open.svg\n9: .. |CI| image:: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/actions/workflows/python-package.yml/badge.svg?branch=develop&event=push\n10: .. |Coveralls| image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open/badge.svg?branch=develop\n11: .. |Version| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/smart-open.svg?logo=pypi&logoColor=white\n12: .. |Python| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/smart-open.svg?logo=python&logoColor=white\n13: .. |Downloads| image:: https://pepy.tech/badge/smart-open/month\n14: .. _License: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/LICENSE\n15: .. _CI: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/actions/workflows/python-package.yml\n16: .. _Coveralls: https://coveralls.io/github/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open?branch=HEAD\n17: .. _Version: https://pypi.org/project/smart-open/\n18: .. _Python: https://pypi.org/project/smart-open/\n19: .. _Downloads: https://pypistats.org/packages/smart-open\n20: \n21: \n22: What?\n23: =====\n24: \n25: ``smart_open`` is a Python 3 library for **efficient streaming of very large files** from/to storages such as S3, GCS, Azure Blob Storage, HDFS, WebHDFS, HTTP, HTTPS, SFTP, or local filesystem. It supports transparent, on-the-fly (de-)compression for a variety of different formats.\n26: \n27: ``smart_open`` is a drop-in replacement for Python's built-in ``open()``: it can do anything ``open`` can (100% compatible, falls back to native ``open`` wherever possible), plus lots of nifty extra stuff on top.\n28: \n29: Why?\n30: ====\n31: \n32: Working with large remote files, for example using Amazon's `boto3 <https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/index.html>`_ Python library, is a pain.\n33: ``boto3``'s ``Object.upload_fileobj()`` and ``Object.download_fileobj()`` methods require gotcha-prone boilerplate to use successfully, such as constructing file-like object wrappers.\n34: ``smart_open`` shields you from that. It builds on boto3 and other remote storage libraries, but offers a **clean unified Pythonic API**. The result is less code for you to write and fewer bugs to make.\n35: \n36: \n37: How?\n38: =====\n39: \n40: ``smart_open`` is well-tested, well-documented, and has a simple Pythonic API:\n41: \n42: \n43: .. _doctools_before_examples:\n44: \n45: .. code-block:: python\n46: \n47:   >>> from smart_open import open\n48:   >>>\n49:   >>> # stream lines from an S3 object\n50:   >>> for line in open('s3://commoncrawl/robots.txt'):\n51:   ...    print(repr(line))\n52:   ...    break\n53:   'User-Agent: *\\n'\n54: \n55:   >>> # stream from/to compressed files, with transparent (de)compression:\n56:   >>> for line in open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.gz', encoding='utf-8'):\n57:   ...    print(repr(line))\n58:   'It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.\\n'\n59:   'Winston Smith, his chin nuzzled into his breast in an effort to escape the vile\\n'\n60:   'wind, slipped quickly through the glass doors of Victory Mansions, though not\\n'\n61:   'quickly enough to prevent a swirl of gritty dust from entering along with him.\\n'\n62: \n63:   >>> # can use context managers too:\n64:   >>> with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.gz') as fin:\n65:   ...    with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.bz2', 'w') as fout:\n66:   ...        for line in fin:\n67:   ...           fout.write(line)\n68:   74\n69:   80\n70:   78\n71:   79\n72: \n73:   >>> # can use any IOBase operations, like seek\n74:   >>> with open('s3://commoncrawl/robots.txt', 'rb') as fin:\n75:   ...     for line in fin:\n76:   ...         print(repr(line.decode('utf-8')))\n77:   ...         break\n78:   ...     offset = fin.seek(0)  # seek to the beginning\n79:   ...     print(fin.read(4))\n80:   'User-Agent: *\\n'\n81:   b'User'\n82: \n83:   >>> # stream from HTTP\n84:   >>> for line in open('http://example.com'):\n85:   ...     print(repr(line[:15]))\n86:   ...     break\n87:   '<!doctype html>'\n88: \n89: .. _doctools_after_examples:\n90: \n91: For more examples of URIs that ``smart_open`` accepts, see `help.txt <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/help.txt>`__ or ``help('smart_open')``.\n92: Some examples::\n93: \n94:     s3://bucket/key\n95:     s3://access_key_id:secret_access_key@bucket/key\n96:     gs://bucket/blob\n97:     azure://bucket/blob\n98:     hdfs://path/file\n99:     ./local/path/file.gz\n100:     file:///home/user/file.bz2\n101:     [ssh|scp|sftp]://username:password@host/path/file\n102: \n103: \n104: Documentation\n105: =============\n106: \n107: The API reference can be viewed at `help.txt <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/help.txt>`__ or using ``help('smart_open')``.\n108: \n109: Installation\n110: ------------\n111: \n112: ``smart_open`` supports a wide range of storage solutions. For all options, see the API reference.\n113: Each individual solution has its own dependencies.\n114: By default, ``smart_open`` does not install any dependencies in order to keep the installation size small.\n115: You can install one or more of these dependencies explicitly using optional dependencies defined in\n116: `pyproject.toml <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/pyproject.toml>`__ :\n117: \n118: .. code-block:: sh\n119: \n120:     pip install 'smart_open[s3,gcs,azure,http,webhdfs,ssh,zst]'\n121: \n122: Or, if you don't mind installing a large number of third party libraries, you can install all dependencies using:\n123: \n124: .. code-block:: sh\n125: \n126:     pip install 'smart_open[all]'\n127: \n128: Built-in help\n129: -------------\n130: \n131: To view the API reference, use the ``help`` python builtin:\n132: \n133: .. code-block:: python\n134: \n135:     help('smart_open')\n136: \n137: or view `help.txt <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/help.txt>`__ in your browser.\n138: \n139: More examples\n140: -------------\n141: \n142: For the sake of simplicity, the examples below assume you have all the dependencies installed, i.e. you have done:\n143: \n144: .. code-block:: sh\n145: \n146:     pip install 'smart_open[all]'\n147: \n148: .. code-block:: python\n149: \n150:     import os, boto3, botocore\n151:     from smart_open import open\n152: \n153:     # stream content *into* S3 (write mode) using a custom client\n154:     # this client is thread-safe ref https://github.com/boto/boto3/blob/1.38.41/docs/source/guide/clients.rst?plain=1#L111\n155:     config = botocore.client.Config(\n156:         max_pool_connections=64,\n157:         tcp_keepalive=True,\n158:         retries={\"max_attempts\": 6, \"mode\": \"adaptive\"},\n159:     )\n160:     client = boto3.Session(\n161:         aws_access_key_id=os.environ['AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID'],\n162:         aws_secret_access_key=os.environ['AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY'],\n163:     ).client(\"s3\", config=config)\n164:     with open('s3://smart-open-py37-benchmark-results/test.txt', 'wb', transport_params={'client': client}) as fout:\n165:         bytes_written = fout.write(b'hello world!')\n166:         print(bytes_written)\n167: \n168:     # perform a single-part upload to S3 (saves billable API requests, and allows seek() before upload)\n169:     with open('s3://smart-open-py37-benchmark-results/test.txt', 'wb', transport_params={'multipart_upload': False}) as fout:\n170:         bytes_written = fout.write(b'hello world!')\n171:         print(bytes_written)\n172:     # now with tempfile.TemporaryFile instead of the default io.BytesIO (to reduce memory footprint)\n173:     import tempfile\n174:     with tempfile.TemporaryFile() as tmp, open('s3://smart-open-py37-benchmark-results/test.txt', 'wb', transport_params={'multipart_upload': False, 'writebuffer': tmp}) as fout:\n175:         bytes_written = fout.write(b'hello world!')\n176:         print(bytes_written)\n177: \n178:     # stream from HDFS\n179:     for line in open('hdfs://user/hadoop/my_file.txt', encoding='utf8'):\n180:         print(line)\n181: \n182:     # stream from WebHDFS\n183:     for line in open('webhdfs://host:port/user/hadoop/my_file.txt'):\n184:         print(line)\n185: \n186:     # stream content *into* HDFS (write mode):\n187:     with open('hdfs://host:port/user/hadoop/my_file.txt', 'wb') as fout:\n188:         fout.write(b'hello world')\n189: \n190:     # stream content *into* WebHDFS (write mode):\n191:     with open('webhdfs://host:port/user/hadoop/my_file.txt', 'wb') as fout:\n192:         fout.write(b'hello world')\n193: \n194:     # stream from a completely custom s3 server, like s3proxy:\n195:     for line in open('s3u://user:secret@host:port@mybucket/mykey.txt'):\n196:         print(line)\n197: \n198:     # Stream to Digital Ocean Spaces bucket providing credentials from boto3 profile\n199:     session = boto3.Session(profile_name='digitalocean')\n200:     client = session.client('s3', endpoint_url='https://ams3.digitaloceanspaces.com')\n201:     transport_params = {'client': client}\n202:     with open('s3://bucket/key.txt', 'wb', transport_params=transport_params) as fout:\n203:         fout.write(b'here we stand')\n204: \n205:     # stream from GCS\n206:     for line in open('gs://my_bucket/my_file.txt'):\n207:         print(line)\n208: \n209:     # stream content *into* GCS (write mode):\n210:     with open('gs://my_bucket/my_file.txt', 'wb') as fout:\n211:         fout.write(b'hello world')\n212: \n213:     # stream from Azure Blob Storage\n214:     connect_str = os.environ['AZURE_STORAGE_CONNECTION_STRING']\n215:     transport_params = {\n216:         'client': azure.storage.blob.BlobServiceClient.from_connection_string(connect_str),\n217:     }\n218:     for line in open('azure://mycontainer/myfile.txt', transport_params=transport_params):\n219:         print(line)\n220: \n221:     # stream content *into* Azure Blob Storage (write mode):\n222:     connect_str = os.environ['AZURE_STORAGE_CONNECTION_STRING']\n223:     transport_params = {\n224:         'client': azure.storage.blob.BlobServiceClient.from_connection_string(connect_str),\n225:     }\n226:     with open('azure://mycontainer/my_file.txt', 'wb', transport_params=transport_params) as fout:\n227:         fout.write(b'hello world')\n228: \n229: Compression Handling\n230: --------------------\n231: \n232: The top-level `compression` parameter controls compression/decompression behavior when reading and writing.\n233: The supported values for this parameter are:\n234: \n235: - ``infer_from_extension`` (default behavior)\n236: - ``disable``\n237: - ``.bz2``\n238: - ``.gz``\n239: - ``.xz``\n240: - ``.zst``\n241: \n242: By default, ``smart_open`` automatically (de)compresses the file if the filename ends with one of these extensions.\n243: `See also <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/smart_open/compression.py>`__\n244: ``smart_open.compression.get_supported_compression_types`` and ``mart_open.compression.register_compressor``.\n245: \n246: .. code-block:: python\n247: \n248:     >>> from smart_open import open\n249:     >>> with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.gz') as fin:\n250:     ...     print(fin.read(32))\n251:     It was a bright cold day in Apri\n252: \n253: You can override this behavior to either disable compression, or explicitly specify the algorithm to use.\n254: To disable compression:\n255: \n256: .. code-block:: python\n257: \n258:     >>> from smart_open import open\n259:     >>> with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.gz', 'rb', compression='disable') as fin:\n260:     ...     print(fin.read(32))\n261:     b'\\x1f\\x8b\\x08\\x08\\x85F\\x94\\\\\\x00\\x031984.txt\\x005\\x8f=r\\xc3@\\x08\\x85{\\x9d\\xe2\\x1d@'\n262: \n263: \n264: To specify the algorithm explicitly (e.g. for non-standard file extensions):\n265: \n266: .. code-block:: python\n267: \n268:     >>> from smart_open import open\n269:     >>> with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.gzip', compression='.gz') as fin:\n270:     ...     print(fin.read(32))\n271:     It was a bright cold day in Apri\n272: \n273: You can also easily add support for other file extensions and compression formats.\n274: For example, to open xz-compressed files:\n275: \n276: .. code-block:: python\n277: \n278:     >>> import lzma, os\n279:     >>> from smart_open import open, register_compressor\n280: \n281:     >>> def _handle_xz(file_obj, mode):\n282:     ...      return lzma.LZMAFile(filename=file_obj, mode=mode)\n283: \n284:     >>> register_compressor('.xz', _handle_xz)\n285: \n286:     >>> with open('tests/test_data/1984.txt.xz') as fin:\n287:     ...     print(fin.read(32))\n288:     It was a bright cold day in Apri\n289: \n290: This is just an example: ``lzma`` is in the standard library and is registered by default.\n291: \n292: Transport-specific Options\n293: --------------------------\n294: \n295: ``smart_open`` supports a wide range of transport options out of the box.\n296: For the full list of supported URI schemes, see `help.txt <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/help.txt>`__ or ``help('smart_open')``.\n297: Some examples::\n298: \n299: - AWS S3 (and any S3-Compatible)\n300: - HTTP, HTTPS (read-only)\n301: - SSH, SCP and SFTP\n302: - HDFS / WebHDFS\n303: - Google Cloud Storage\n304: - Azure Blob Storage\n305: \n306: Each option involves setting up its own set of parameters.\n307: For example, for accessing S3, you often need to set up authentication, like API keys or a profile name.\n308: ``smart_open``'s ``open`` function accepts a keyword argument ``transport_params`` which accepts additional parameters for the transport layer.\n309: Here are some examples of using this parameter:\n310: \n311: .. code-block:: python\n312: \n313:   >>> import boto3\n314:   >>> fin = open('s3://commoncrawl/robots.txt', transport_params=dict(client=boto3.client('s3')))\n315:   >>> fin = open('s3://commoncrawl/robots.txt', transport_params=dict(buffer_size=1024))\n316: \n317: For the full list of keyword arguments supported by each transport option, see `help.txt <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/help.txt>`__ or ``help('smart_open')``.\n318: \n319: .. code-block:: python\n320: \n321:   help('smart_open.open')\n322: \n323: S3 Credentials\n324: --------------\n325: \n326: ``smart_open`` uses the ``boto3`` library to talk to S3.\n327: ``boto3`` has several `mechanisms <https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/guide/configuration.html>`__ for determining the credentials to use.\n328: By default, ``smart_open`` will defer to ``boto3`` and let the latter take care of the credentials.\n329: There are several ways to override this behavior.\n330: \n331: The first is to pass a ``boto3.Client`` object as a transport parameter to the ``open`` function.\n332: You can customize the credentials when constructing the session for the client.\n333: ``smart_open`` will then use the session when talking to S3.\n334: \n335: .. code-block:: python\n336: \n337:     session = boto3.Session(\n338:         aws_access_key_id=ACCESS_KEY,\n339:         aws_secret_access_key=SECRET_KEY,\n340:         aws_session_token=SESSION_TOKEN,\n341:     )\n342:     client = session.client('s3', endpoint_url=..., config=...)\n343:     fin = open('s3://bucket/key', transport_params={'client': client})\n344: \n345: Your second option is to specify the credentials within the S3 URL itself:\n346: \n347: .. code-block:: python\n348: \n349:     fin = open('s3://aws_access_key_id:aws_secret_access_key@bucket/key', ...)\n350: \n351: *Important*: The two methods above are **mutually exclusive**. If you pass an AWS client *and* the URL contains credentials, ``smart_open`` will ignore the latter.\n352: \n353: *Important*: ``smart_open`` ignores configuration files from the older ``boto`` library.\n354: Port your old ``boto`` settings to ``boto3`` in order to use them with ``smart_open``.\n355: \n356: S3 Advanced Usage\n357: -----------------\n358: \n359: Additional keyword arguments can be propagated to the boto3 methods that are used by ``smart_open`` under the hood using the ``client_kwargs`` transport parameter.\n360: \n361: For instance, to upload a blob with Metadata, ACL, StorageClass, these keyword arguments can be passed to ``create_multipart_upload`` (`docs <https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/reference/services/s3.html#S3.Client.create_multipart_upload>`__).\n362: \n363: .. code-block:: python\n364: \n365:     kwargs = {'Metadata': {'version': 2}, 'ACL': 'authenticated-read', 'StorageClass': 'STANDARD_IA'}\n366:     fout = open('s3://bucket/key', 'wb', transport_params={'client_kwargs': {'S3.Client.create_multipart_upload': kwargs}})\n367: \n368: Iterating Over an S3 Bucket's Contents\n369: --------------------------------------\n370: \n371: Since going over all (or select) keys in an S3 bucket is a very common operation, there's also an extra function ``smart_open.s3.iter_bucket()`` that does this efficiently, **processing the bucket keys in parallel** (using multiprocessing):\n372: \n373: .. code-block:: python\n374: \n375:   >>> from smart_open import s3\n376:   >>> # we use workers=1 for reproducibility; you should use as many workers as you have cores\n377:   >>> bucket = 'silo-open-data'\n378:   >>> prefix = 'Official/annual/monthly_rain/'\n379:   >>> for key, content in s3.iter_bucket(bucket, prefix=prefix, accept_key=lambda key: '/201' in key, workers=1, key_limit=3):\n380:   ...     print(key, round(len(content) / 2**20))\n381:   Official/annual/monthly_rain/2010.monthly_rain.nc 13\n382:   Official/annual/monthly_rain/2011.monthly_rain.nc 13\n383:   Official/annual/monthly_rain/2012.monthly_rain.nc 13\n384: \n385: GCS Credentials\n386: ---------------\n387: ``smart_open`` uses the ``google-cloud-storage`` library to talk to GCS.\n388: ``google-cloud-storage`` uses the ``google-cloud`` package under the hood to handle authentication.\n389: There are several `options <https://googleapis.dev/python/google-api-core/latest/auth.html>`__ to provide\n390: credentials.\n391: By default, ``smart_open`` will defer to ``google-cloud-storage`` and let it take care of the credentials.\n392: \n393: To override this behavior, pass a ``google.cloud.storage.Client`` object as a transport parameter to the ``open`` function.\n394: You can `customize the credentials <https://googleapis.dev/python/storage/latest/client.html>`__\n395: when constructing the client. ``smart_open`` will then use the client when talking to GCS. To follow allow with\n396: the example below, `refer to Google's guide <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/reference/libraries#setting_up_authentication>`__\n397: to setting up GCS authentication with a service account.\n398: \n399: .. code-block:: python\n400: \n401:     import os\n402:     from google.cloud.storage import Client\n403:     service_account_path = os.environ['GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS']\n404:     client = Client.from_service_account_json(service_account_path)\n405:     fin = open('gs://gcp-public-data-landsat/index.csv.gz', transport_params=dict(client=client))\n406: \n407: If you need more credential options, you can create an explicit ``google.auth.credentials.Credentials`` object\n408: and pass it to the Client. To create an API token for use in the example below, refer to the\n409: `GCS authentication guide <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/authentication#apiauth>`__.\n410: \n411: .. code-block:: python\n412: \n413: \timport os\n414: \tfrom google.auth.credentials import Credentials\n415: \tfrom google.cloud.storage import Client\n416: \ttoken = os.environ['GOOGLE_API_TOKEN']\n417: \tcredentials = Credentials(token=token)\n418: \tclient = Client(credentials=credentials)\n419: \tfin = open('gs://gcp-public-data-landsat/index.csv.gz', transport_params={'client': client})\n420: \n421: GCS Advanced Usage\n422: ------------------\n423: \n424: Additional keyword arguments can be propagated to the GCS open method (`docs <https://cloud.google.com/python/docs/reference/storage/latest/google.cloud.storage.blob.Blob#google_cloud_storage_blob_Blob_open>`__), which is used by ``smart_open`` under the hood, using the ``blob_open_kwargs`` transport parameter.\n425: \n426: Additionally keyword arguments can be propagated to the GCS ``get_blob`` method (`docs <https://cloud.google.com/python/docs/reference/storage/latest/google.cloud.storage.bucket.Bucket#google_cloud_storage_bucket_Bucket_get_blob>`__) when in a read-mode, using the ``get_blob_kwargs`` transport parameter.\n427: \n428: Additional blob properties (`docs <https://cloud.google.com/python/docs/reference/storage/latest/google.cloud.storage.blob.Blob#properties>`__) can be set before an upload, as long as they are not read-only, using the ``blob_properties`` transport parameter.\n429: \n430: .. code-block:: python\n431: \n432:     open_kwargs = {'predefined_acl': 'authenticated-read'}\n433:     properties = {'metadata': {'version': 2}, 'storage_class': 'COLDLINE'}\n434:     fout = open('gs://bucket/key', 'wb', transport_params={'blob_open_kwargs': open_kwargs, 'blob_properties': properties})\n435: \n436: Azure Credentials\n437: -----------------\n438: \n439: ``smart_open`` uses the ``azure-storage-blob`` library to talk to Azure Blob Storage.\n440: By default, ``smart_open`` will defer to ``azure-storage-blob`` and let it take care of the credentials.\n441: \n442: Azure Blob Storage does not have any ways of inferring credentials therefore, passing a ``azure.storage.blob.BlobServiceClient``\n443: object as a transport parameter to the ``open`` function is required.\n444: You can `customize the credentials <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-samples-python#authentication>`__\n445: when constructing the client. ``smart_open`` will then use the client when talking to. To follow allow with\n446: the example below, `refer to Azure's guide <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/storage-quickstart-blobs-python#copy-your-credentials-from-the-azure-portal>`__\n447: to setting up authentication.\n448: \n449: .. code-block:: python\n450: \n451:     import os\n452:     from azure.storage.blob import BlobServiceClient\n453:     azure_storage_connection_string = os.environ['AZURE_STORAGE_CONNECTION_STRING']\n454:     client = BlobServiceClient.from_connection_string(azure_storage_connection_string)\n455:     fin = open('azure://my_container/my_blob.txt', transport_params={'client': client})\n456: \n457: If you need more credential options, refer to the\n458: `Azure Storage authentication guide <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-samples-python#authentication>`__.\n459: \n460: Azure Advanced Usage\n461: --------------------\n462: \n463: Additional keyword arguments can be propagated to the ``commit_block_list`` method (`docs <https://azuresdkdocs.blob.core.windows.net/$web/python/azure-storage-blob/12.14.1/azure.storage.blob.html#azure.storage.blob.BlobClient.commit_block_list>`__), which is used by ``smart_open`` under the hood for uploads, using the ``blob_kwargs`` transport parameter.\n464: \n465: .. code-block:: python\n466: \n467:     kwargs = {'metadata': {'version': 2}}\n468:     fout = open('azure://container/key', 'wb', transport_params={'blob_kwargs': kwargs})\n469: \n470: Drop-in replacement of ``pathlib.Path.open``\n471: --------------------------------------------\n472: \n473: ``smart_open.open`` can also be used with ``Path`` objects.\n474: The built-in `Path.open()` is not able to read text from compressed files, so use ``patch_pathlib`` to replace it with `smart_open.open()` instead.\n475: This can be helpful when e.g. working with compressed files.\n476: \n477: .. code-block:: python\n478: \n479:     >>> from pathlib import Path\n480:     >>> from smart_open.smart_open_lib import patch_pathlib\n481:     >>>\n482:     >>> _ = patch_pathlib()  # replace `Path.open` with `smart_open.open`\n483:     >>>\n484:     >>> path = Path(\"tests/test_data/crime-and-punishment.txt.gz\")\n485:     >>>\n486:     >>> with path.open(\"r\") as infile:\n487:     ...     print(infile.readline()[:41])\n488:     В начале июля, в чрезвычайно жаркое время\n489: \n490: How do I ...?\n491: =============\n492: \n493: See `this document <howto.md>`__.\n494: \n495: Extending ``smart_open``\n496: ========================\n497: \n498: See `this document <extending.md>`__.\n499: \n500: Testing ``smart_open``\n501: ======================\n502: \n503: ``smart_open`` comes with a comprehensive suite of unit tests.\n504: Before you can run the test suite, install the test dependencies::\n505: \n506:     pip install -e .[test]\n507: \n508: Now, you can run the unit tests::\n509: \n510:     pytest tests\n511: \n512: The tests are also run automatically with `GitHub Actions <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/actions/workflows/python-package.yml>`_ on every commit push & pull request.\n513: \n514: Comments, bug reports\n515: =====================\n516: \n517: ``smart_open`` lives on `Github <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open>`_. You can file\n518: issues or pull requests there. Suggestions, pull requests and improvements welcome!\n519: \n520: ----------------\n521: \n522: ``smart_open`` is open source software released under the `MIT license <https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/LICENSE>`_.\n523: Copyright (c) 2015-now `Radim Řehůřek <https://radimrehurek.com>`_.\n\n(End of file - total 523 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"======================================================\nsmart_open — utils for streaming large files in Python\n======================================================\n\n\n|License|_ |CI|_ |Coveralls|_ |Version|_ |Python|_ |Downloads|_\n\n.. |License| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/smart_open.svg\n.. |CI| image:: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/actions/workflows/python-package.yml/badge.svg?branch=develop&event=push\n.. |Coveralls| image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open/badge.svg?branch=develop\n.. |Version| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/smart-open.svg?logo=pypi&logoColor=white\n.. |Python| image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/smart-open.svg?logo=python&logoColor=white\n.. |Downloads| image:: https://pepy.tech/badge/smart-open/month\n.. _License: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/blob/master/LICENSE\n.. _CI: https://github.com/piskvorky/smart_open/actions/workflows/python-package.yml\n.. _Coveralls: https://coveralls.io/github/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open?branch=HEAD\n.. _Version: https://pypi.org/project/smart-open/\n.. _Python: https://pypi.org/project/smart-open/\n.. _Downloads: https://pypistats.org/packages/smart-open\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1775787714419,"end":1775787714431}}}]}
